Today is Christmas, and I always feel a little listless and sad. I'm not sure why, but after the hoarding of gifts and the frenzy of unwrapping and thanking and re-examining gifts, I always want to just crawl back into bed and sleep. Luckily I am at my parents house - the sanctuary to do that kind of thing. James Taylor's new Christmas album fills the living room and the smell of stuffing and turkey and gravy fill the kitchen, and everyone is ripe with new books, CDs and DVDs. The cats outside are howling at Wicket, and Daddy is somewhere smoking a cigar.&nbsp; It's almost noon, but it's like I have been awake forever.&nbsp;

I didn't sleep much last night - not because of my excitement that Santa is coming, but because I'm troubled with the uncertainty of my future. Which is odd, considering I have always been uncertain of my future, but now that I'm older (I will laugh at this when I'm 40) I just feel like I can't make too many more mistakes or take to many&nbsp; chances. And I miss Robert. The night before last, I watched The Sound of Music with Daddy and Patti, and I couldn't stop thinking of him. But when he called, there was no time to really talk. He's in Boston and very very busy seeing everyone and doesn't have the time to really catch up on much. Part of me feels foolish that I am expecting to much - I'm just bummed he can't be here, that we can't be together. I suppose it's not such a big deal, he told me last night that I was fretting over nothing. "People have to deal with this all the time...sorry I'm not as bummed about it as you"&nbsp; I"m sorry too.&nbsp;

I called my mother, who is alone on Christmas. She spent a lot of time putting together a box for me this year, with lots of sweet things like shirts and jewelery. She even remembered Robert - I am sure he will be touched by that. She's going to see Betty, my late Grandfather's lady friend, today in the hospital, and they are going to have Christmas dinner with her. I never quiet understood the whole Christmas Dinner thing. I am just not that big of a fan of Turkey and dressing, but every year, it's always really good. My favorites are all the sides, like mashed potatoes and green bean cassarole. Robert says he makes a great Turkey. I'm sure he is enjoying one now, wherever he is. Or maybe he's at Mass with his Daughter and the rest of his family. Not having a big family it's hard to imagine. Ben had a huge family, but they were always so noisy and wild. There were over 20 kids and of course, Ben and I were there to babysit while the adults got to relax. That got pretty old, even though I really love kids. Not only that, but there was always some drama going on with either Rick, or his Wife, or with Grandmother and someone. I'm so glad I never have to deal with that again. I am actually very blessed.

So this year I got a chance at a new life - and that has been the greatest gift of all. I have a family (however scattered and small) that loves me very much, I have friends that I can laugh and cry with, and I have the kind of love that I never thought possible, even better than in the movies. And I have the cutest dog on the face of this planet. What more can a girl ask for?&nbsp;

My wishes for everyone else is that they get their Christmas Miracle today. I hope your year is filled with lots of laughter and love. And cheese, can't have too much of that! Merry Christmas, and may God Bless us, Everyone!

Michaela

And everything looks different somehow. I know my immidiate future, but somehow I don't feel much better. Maybe it's because&nbsp;I haven't slept much.&nbsp;

It's been a busy week. I went to the Counting Crows/Goo Goo Dolls concert last night, so I was out pretty late. It was neat - I didn't get to hear "accidentally in love" but I did hear the most amazing version of "Round Here" that I had ever - and will ever - hear. It almost made up for it.&nbsp; My favorite part was The goo goo dolls singing "better days" - it was truly awesome.&nbsp;

Anyway, things are looking up - or, they should be. The divorce stuff is all but over - thank God. My parents are coming to visit soon and there is an Awesome dance next weekend in college station that should be fun. AND tonight I am going to see Jack's Mannequin - that's right, whose lead singer is the one who penned "Konstantine" which always reminds me of a really sad night in September.&nbsp;

With all the whirlwind of things, I should be happier and more excited, but I think I'm just overwhelmed into feeling nothing.&nbsp;

That, or it's the steroids.

Ah, the craziness has resumed. It's summer. It's hot as hell. My electric bill is rivaling my car payment. I need to get my ass to a gym. But then I would just sweat more than I already am. Not cool, man, not cool.

I haven't heard from Tim in a while, but as far as the rest of my life, everyone else seems to be fantastic. Well, everyone but my mom. She's having a lot of pain and back&nbsp;issues. And to top that off, she has two occlusions in her eyes and that could mean anything from Lupos to Luekemia to nothing at all. She could go blind any minute or she could be just fine. My poor mother. She never gets a break. And if that wasn't bad enough, my brother got violent with her and she doesn't know what to do. On the upside, she now realises what a headcase he is and that he really needs help, but now she's just at a loss as to what to do. And I don't know if, when the time comes again, she will do what she needs to do - which is call the cops and arrest him.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Let's see. What else. Wilber, my lovely Wilber, seems to have found his match - at last. And she seems to like him back, and I'm so very excited about this! He met her on the dance floor - something he always said would happen - and she likes punk music, but has a moral compass. All good things for my Wilber. She's younger than him by a few years, but she seems very nice - and more importantly, Wilber and her seem to be getting along beautifully. YAY!!!

And Byron seems to have himself a girlie as well. Everyone is hooking up these days. And while I am so very excited about these things, I am bittersweetened as well. As an angel, I have to let go of "my boys" when it's time to let them go. Some boys are harder to let go than others. Sometimes it takes me pushing them away; sometimes, I just need to disappear for a few months. Sometimes, it happens before they even realize I was ever there. It's part of the job, and it's silly for me to think that it won't happen. But I'm happy for them. It's a very exciting thing, to like someone and have them like you back. It's lovely. And it's summer, so it matched the season.It's hard to let go of people you care so much about, and let them out into the wild of this world. But everything is inevitable.

I love my life. I do. It's broke and it's hard to make it through the day sometimes, but I love it. I have so much love in my life, so many things to be greatful for. Everyday I thank God for the gifts of my life - there are too many to count. And I am so, so grateful to have people who love me so, who will always be there for me, people who understand me but love me anyway. That is all people really want, in life. To be understood, and despite of that, be loved. That's why Jesus is such a popular guy.&nbsp;

I just read this article about this over 50 yr old woman in a black bikini. Her mother, noting that she no longer had the 20 something figure that normally goes with that style of bathing suit, criticized her and told her not to wear anything like that again.&nbsp;

And you know what? She went right on ahead and wore what she wanted. Because she was comfortable with what her body was.&nbsp;

Women are always in competition. Seriously, I don't know of any women who hasn't felt a twinge of jealousy when someone smaller/cuter/younger was in the room asking for an opinion. That jealousy is the reason why I never ask my Stepmother, Patti, for advice on what color dress to buy, or how long my skirt should be. Because she would say "black, and the longer the better", rather than the truth. We have never agreed on what made me look good growing up, and when I think back on how she would reason with me that I really needed to stay away from reds and not show off what legs I have got, it used to hurt me a lot.&nbsp; But I know she loves me.&nbsp;The jealousy that women have isn't rational and it has nothing to do with your feelings about a person.&nbsp;

Personally, I have been on a long journey to be ok with the body I was given. I was not meant to ever be a size 4. And you know what? I am not really as small as I have been in the past, but I feel better about where I am and who I am - and people lately have just piled on the compliments. I don't have much to say when they ask what I have done - I simply like my body more now. I have small feet with pink toes (who all have names, by the way). I have shapely legs that allow me to dance with people I love. I have a tummy that reminds me of those reniassance paintings (minus the belly ring I got with my mother In February to celebrate my curviness). I have arms and hands that allow me to give great massages. I have my mother's golden crown of hair, and blue eyes. I was given this body for a reason. And I love it. I love it even though it's bigger than the emaciated models tripping down the runways. I love it becasue it's mine - it's the greatest intrument I will ever own.&nbsp;

I have a two piece bathing suite. I wear it whenever I can. It's not a bikini, but rather a "tankini" that gives me more coverage on top (which I need, thanks to the Augustine genes). But it shows the belly I used to hate, and the nonextistent hips I used to try to compensate for. Not anymore. I wear red every chance I can, and I show off the skin I love (although tasefully). And I am loved. People love me because of who I am, not because of a number size I wear. Why do we as girls have to care so much about what people think? And why can't we be celebrated for being mothers and sisters and daughters and lovers - yes, even at size 14 and up?

We can, and we will. And I'm going to start - right now.

So last night I had the strangest dream. I dreamt that a bunch of swing dancing friends were at my new apartment (okay, not so new, but whatever) and they were all helping me paint it up and make it pretty since they all found out about Ben and that we are separating. And these people, although they were my friends at the time, I have no idea who they were - I didn't recognize any of them. And there was this awful wallpaper on my walls (not the case in reality) and they were stripping it off and painting my room this lovely sky blue. And I think my dad was there for a while, just being supportive and all. And then, Ben showed up. And he was the Ben I remember liking, all nice and wanting to talk about things. And I was angry because he just expected to go back to living in my house and being the way we used to be, and I just couldn't ever do that again. And I remember asking him about Corrin, if something fell apart there, and then he turned into the Ben I remember most, and then things got ugly. He finally left me and all my friends, and we exchanged some horrible things that would not be fair to mention here. But then, as I had slammed the door, my friends and I went into my bed room to watch him from the window, and he was running around with a knife. Very Strange.&nbsp;

Today has been pretty lovely. I am going to Austin this weekend and I can't wait. I'm going to go see Robert's nephew for his 2nd birthday party - a very big deal since I've never been to a child's birthday party before - and just hang out around Austin. Maybe I will get a tattoo - tee hee! Ok, maybe not yet, but I have been thinking about it....although, I don't know where I would put it on my body that I wouldn't regret later. That's the only thing about tatoos - you don't want to get one you are going to tire of or have to cover up sometime. Still thinking about where I would put one and exactly what I would get.&nbsp;

The day has gone by rather quickly. Becky, my boss, took me and the girls (Laura and Cinthya) out for a lovely lunch at the Striphouse Steak joint down town - very very nice. I ate way too much but it was worth it - soo good!&nbsp;

Now, however, I am fighting to stay awake and finish out my day. And then it's off to Austin for a long weekend of relaxation and birthday cake.

And tattoos.

