It's good to be back where I know my life. It's nice to see a familiar face and not feel like I've been walking around in a trance. This weekend was long. Sunday night, things got a little sober. My parents, who love me dearly, can't seem to make up their mind on what I should do with my life. three months ago they didn't want me to date anyone....for a year. Now, they want me to...ehem...date lots and lots of people for a year before settling down again. Now, by this year, I mean a year from when my divorce is final, which could be months and months from now. I am told by Patti that I will feel freeer and more liberated than I do now, just because a paper that I didn't really agree with in the first place will be signed, sealed and delivered to go rest on some library shelf. I mean, she was talking to the girl who didn't want to get legally married in the first place - THAT's how much I value a peice of paper. And I could be wrong, but I don't think she had any place to talk, given what she did during her 20 or so years of being techinically married to someone. That didn't stop her from having very nice, long lasting relationships with others. And then I realised that I need to quit trying to get approval from people who simply will not give it - not on my terms, anyway. It was a sad day, because I had these hopes of someday getting it right for all of us. Oh well. I know&nbsp;they love me. Sometimes they just don't make the best choices when it comes to communicating their feelings on a given subject.&nbsp;

 Monday dad and I went out to play pool - and that was fun. We drank a lot, I got lots of free drinks from a guy named Bill who used to substitute teach at my high school (strange? yeah, a bit...but the drinks were nice). Tuesday I left as early as I could, which ended up being around noon, to go to Austin to see Tim. Tim, who was nice enough to listen to me blab on and on about parents and relationships and such. He's the best. We ate at Carraba's and then it started to get kinda stormy so I went back to houston, where I met up with Tricia and Jim at my place. We watched Tap, which was neat because Tricia never had seen it, and we ate lots of ice cream and snackies. Yummy.&nbsp;

Yesterday, my world came back into focus. And while it was a long day, it ended beautifully, with me billowing in my bed and reading and lounging and loving the world, loving my life, once again.&nbsp;

And now I just want to get out of her, drive home and be there again, be me again, be in my life. It's getting gloomy, I better head out before it pours.

Last night I saw Cars with Robert and Wilber. I have to apologize to Tim, because he really wanted the next movie that I see be Tokyo Drift - and I just don't think I can bring myself to watch that one. We had a blast - I thought it was one of the best films Pixar has done in a while. I mean, they are all fantastic, but this one just melted me away - it was really hilarious. And there was this older car, Mater, that seriously stole half of Robert's lines. It was so funny to watch - we laughed and laughed. It was great for WIlber to meet Robert finally - we had dinner at Logans and it was pretty yummy.&nbsp; I got to see Wilber's fish tank - it's pretty cool. I don't know much about&nbsp; brackish water (like the spelling, for example) but the fish looked happy and of course Kitty was always happy to see me.&nbsp;

Things are looking up all the time - I have so much to be grateful for. I'm going away for the long holiday weekend. I can't wait to see my parents - I have missed them so much. We are going to celebrate father's day and play some pool - ah yes, the wonder's of pool. I really love playing, my daddy taught me how when I was around 11 or 12 and we've been playing ever since. I was one a league for a year and a half with "the boys" (Kenneth and Steve) and we always had such a good time.&nbsp; I think of them all the time.

My parent's house, as I have said before, is like my home away from home - it really is an oasis of books, music, and really awesome Coffee. I plan on doing as little as possible when I get there - and it's going to be lovely. And it's not such a bad drive, even though it can be long. When Rita hit, that was the longest drive of my life. But it's always worth it - waking up in the morning, padding down the stairs to see my dad's famous coffee sitting in a mug with a piece of paper over it with my name inscribed. When I was growing up, my daddy would leave me little notes in the morning saying "Good morning! I love you!" because he would leave long before I got up for school.&nbsp;

I often wonder about being a parent. I wonder if I wil be any good at it. People call me a natural mother, but I don't know - I can be so selfish sometimes. And you know, I'm older than a lot of people who have kids. And I know now I'm not ready. I mean, sometimes you aren't given a choice, but I hope and pray that I'm as good as my daddy was. I mean, I never knew anything about what was going on in his life, if he had problems at work, if he and my mother were screaming at each other in a lawyer's office. I never knew hw it all happened. And we talked all the time - but it was always about me and what my plans were with me life and what I wanted and how I felt. And he drew me pictures in the morning and flew kites with me and taught me to play pool and to spell and to drive. And I turned out ok, I think. I mean, I never made any huge mistakes that weren't repairable and fairly normal. I did some stupid stuff, and I got really lucky, but I don't know if that's different than most people's stories.&nbsp;

Maybe I will Allison this weekend - that would be lovely - I have missed her so. I am not sure where she is living now, I think she's still in Arlington, so maybe she will not make it back for the holiday. I think of her all the time, and although neither one of us stays in touch as much as we like, I hope she knows that i'm always here for her and that I love her lots and lots.&nbsp;

So much love today - must be because I have had the best two days in a while. Ah, I love...I love so much. And although it's not "normal", I wouldn't change it for the world.

Nothing in particular, and everything in between. After an evening of just doing nothing - ok, not nothing, I did manage to watch The Closer on TNT which I had recorded - I love that show. I'm not really sure why either, because sometimes it just doesn't make any sense. But I like the woman Brenda Leigh, played by Kyra Sedgwick. I think she's a pretty good actress, and she's in a league of her own being married (for a really, really long time) to Kevin Bacon. Anyway, she's very powerful and kicks some serious ass. And i would have liked to have been that cool, calm, and collected. She must be so much fun to play with.&nbsp;

God smiled on me last night. I was feeling icky and unsure and over all NOT good but I'm all better now. I like&nbsp;being able to be so honest about how I feel and have that be ok - no matter what it is that I am feeling. I have always been a big talker, a big communication person, but sometimes the rules in communication are hard to follow. That makes it tough to work things through. Anyway, I'm glad that everything is better now - it's the scariest feeling in the world when you think that you've become the one thing you didn't want to be.&nbsp;

Today is Bob's Birthday. Bob is a laywer at my office. We are taking him out to some vietnamese restaurant for lunch. I am excited but I'm worried too - I like to try new things, but there is definitely a cap on my adventuresomenes. Is that even a real word? What I mean is that some days I am not ready to venture in to the unknown, and other days I am all for it. I'm very strange that way. This weekend, for example, I did nothing "normal" on Saturday. Everything was a new adventure, a new dish to eat, a new group of people to hang out with and talk to. And it was lovely. I cannot say that I would have liked to have had that adventer again on Sunday. Being fearless and trying new things can be exhausting.

The day is clear and bright, but there isn't much more to say now. I will write more later.

This weekend was long and yet not long enough - but I am sure that's nothing new to anyone. A brief synopsis follows.


Friday I did a whole lot of nothing. I worked out and started the movie "Angel Heart" - a 1980's thriller staring Mickey Rourke and the older daughter from the Cosby Show&nbsp; and Robert Dinero. It was the last movie Cosby show girl did before getting kicked off the Cosby show. It could have been because there is this very graphic sene where blood is pouring down the walls, but whatever. It was interesting and the last 10 seconds scared me enough to make it hard for me to sleep.&nbsp;

Saturday was all new for me. I went to midnight comics and played Hackmaster (a D&amp;D kind of game) with Robert and his gaming friends. It was supposed to run from noon to four, but of course, being gamers, no one showed up until one. So it lasted untill 5:30 and then Robert and I went to dinner with a friend of his at work. We ate down in China town at some little bistro - it was really good. Noodles and chicken and coffee milk tea - I hadn't had anything we ordered before. We stayed there talking until almost midnight, and then I went home and finished Angelheart and not sleep.&nbsp;

Sunday was nice - I rearranged my kitchen some and came up with some neat ideas of how to use my new appliances and maximize counter space. Then I went to lunch with Tim. He was in town for the weekend and so I got to spend a few hours with him. We went to lunch and then went for Milk Tea - a tradition since our days in Austin. Tim keeps asking me to move there, which I wouldn't really mind doing except for the fact that my LIFE is here. We talked a bit about Ben - Tim hasn't spoken to him in a long time, but was surprised that the divorce wasn't final yet. Why? Because he's already living with another woman. Yes, THAT woman. And poor Tim was like "I thought you knew, I'm so sorry." It was kind of funny because I am supposed to be the one who ran off with another man and yet he's telling everyone he can about the great sex he's having and how he's so much happier. And I do hope he's happy. I hope he's so happy he gets over trying to keep me from divorcing him&nbsp; - because his actions are rather paraoxical. He's so happy to be away from me, but he's making it harder for me to sever myself from him. Makes so sense to me, but then, as Tim said "he's really a kid most of the time."

Sunday night, the boys from College Station (er, Waco/Dallas now that it's summer) came into town, so I danced with them for an hour. It was SO great to see Matt and Byron again - they are just the nicest guys ever! And I got to see Daniel and Woody and Richard and Mark - I wore Mark's belt again because my pants kept falling down. I'm getting smaller all the time, which is great, except that I forget to wear a belt when I go dancing and they are so loose they fall. Thank GOD for Mark and his belt - he's saved me numerous times!~

Last night, I had a dream about working in a Law Office. It was strange. I was there for about half the day when I realised I hadn't quit my old job at Myron Steves, so it was a messy situation. Those dreams are hard for me, I used to dream them about Ben, now just about my job. Strange strange stuff man.&nbsp;

So that's all for now - will write more later.
